"Tewksbury C.E., Van Miegroet H.","Soil organic carbon dynamics along a climatic gradient in a southern Appalachian spruce-fir forest",2007,"Canadian Journal of Forest Research","37","7",,"1161","1172",,,10.1139/X06-317,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-35848971024&partnerID=40&md5=3f9fa8b0f21b618439f19026777b0fe1","Utah State University, Department Wildland Resources, 5230 Old Main Hill, Logan, UT 84322-5230, United States; University of Arizona, School of Natural Resources, 325 Biological Sciences East, Tucson, AZ 85721-0043, United States","Tewksbury, C.E., Utah State University, Department Wildland Resources, 5230 Old Main Hill, Logan, UT 84322-5230, United States, University of Arizona, School of Natural Resources, 325 Biological Sciences East, Tucson, AZ 85721-0043, United States; Van Miegroet, H., Utah State University, Department Wildland Resources, 5230 Old Main Hill, Logan, UT 84322-5230, United States","A field study was conducted in a high-elevation spruce-fir (Picea rubens Sarg. - Abies fraseri (Pursh.) Poir) forest in the Great Smoky Mountains National Park to assess the effect of temperature on soil C storage and dynamics. In eight plots along an elevation gradient (1500-1900 m), we measured soil temperature, forest floor and mineral soil C, litter decomposition, soil respiration, and forest floor mean residence time. Mean annual soil temperature and annual degree-days above 5°C were inversely correlated with elevation. Total soil C (166-241 Mg·ha-1) showed no trend with elevation, while forest floor C accumulation (16.3-35.9 Mg·ha-1) decreased significantly with elevation. Carbon dynamics did not follow a consistent elevation pattern; however, the cooler upper elevations showed the lowest C turnover as indicated by the lowest needle decomposition rate (k = 0.0231·year-1) and the longest mean residence time of forest floor C (22 years). Mean annual CO2 efflux from the soil (1020-1830 kg C·ha-1·year-1) was negatively correlated with mean annual soil temperatures and annual degree-days above 5°C. This gradient study offers useful insights into C release patterns under future warming scenarios, and suggests that the highest elevation may be most susceptible to global warming. © 2007 NRC.",,"Forestry; Global warming; Thermal effects; Elevation gradient; Litter decomposition; Soil respiration; Soil temperature; Organic carbon; carbon cycle; carbon sequestration; coniferous forest; decomposition; elevation; forest floor; forest soil; leaf litter; organic carbon; residence time; soil carbon; soil respiration; soil temperature; temperature effect; Carbon; Forestry; Great Smoky Mountains National Park; North America; United States; Abies; Abies fraseri; Picea; Picea rubens",,,,,,"Admundson, R., The carbon budget in soils (2001) Annu. Rev. Earth Planet. Sci, 29, pp. 535-562; Albritton, D.L., Meira Filho, L.G., Cubasch, U., Dai, X., Ding, Y., Griggs, D.J., Hewitson, B., Houghton, J.T., Isaksen, I., Karl, T., McFarland, M., Meleshko, V.P., Mitchell, J.F.B., Noguer, M., Nyenzi, B.S., Oppenheimer, M., Penner, J.E., Pollonais, S., Stocker, T., and Trenberth, K.E. 2001. Technical summary of the Working Group 1 Report. In Climate change 2001: The scientific basis. Contribution of Working Group I to the Third Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change. Edited by R.A. Houghton. Cambridge University Press, Cambridge. pp. 21-83Alexander, M., (1977) Introduction to soil microbiology, , 2nd ed. John Wiley & Sons, Inc, Indianapolis, Ind; Barker, M., Van Miegroet, H., Nicholas, N.S., Creed, I.F., Variation in overstory nitrogen uptake in a small, high-elevation southern Appalachian spruce-fir watershed (2002) Can. J. For. Res, 32, pp. 1741-1752. , doi:10.1139/x02-098; Blake, G.R., and Hartge, K.H. 1986. Bulk density. In Methods of soil analysis. Part I. Physical and mineralogical methods. Edited by A. Klute. Agronomy 9. Agronomy Society of America, Madison, Wisc. pp. 363-375Bolstad, P.V., Vose, 